                    </div>
                    <span>I am well educated but have been stuck in jobs for which I've been overqualified.  And then unemployed ultra long term in the latest structural economic crises.  Much of my work life, I have taken advice from books written BY management FOR management, and applied it down to my situation. With a moderate amount of success, I might add.  I wrote aggressive cover letters looking for jobs, campaigned fiercely for jobs in the past, for example.
<br />  
<br />THIS IS ONE OF THOSE TYPES OF BOOKS.  There is a grain of truth in every situation, just a matter of degree.  SO THESE BOOKS ARE TO BE TAKEN WITH A GRAIN OF SALT, BUT LEARNED FROM!!  
<br />
<br />Yes, books like these are absolutely just like magazines like The Utne Reader, which look a little down on daughters of the working class and the "choices" they do not have to make but "should" (but that's as far as I will go with all that--irrespective of where one is politically on this--privilege exists everywhere in the political spectrum).
<br />
<br />At 50 years old, I am about to emerge from underground.  I am probably one of the "invisible homeless", having lived and living in various relatives' abodes, for longer than I care to think about.
<br />
<br />I would be taking psychotropic drugs right now if I took any of this (stuff happening outside myself) to heart!
<br />
<br />First, I lost 60 pounds and managed to keep it off this time.  Then, I sort of changed careers.  The future is uncertain, as I am not working full time right now, but there is hope for full time in the future.
<br />
<br />And some hope for my choices ...
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Nice to know there are others out there!</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-23</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I picked up this book at a time when I was really struggling for a direction and purpose in my life. This book showed me that I'm not in alone in this quest. Po Bronson traveled across the United States to hear and document the stories of those who yearned for something more, those who tried to find it and succeed, those who tried to find it but failed and those who simply lived with the yearning.
<br />
<br />'What Should I Do With My Life?' is not a book for everyone. It doesn't spell out for us what we need to do or what we should do. It just gives us a very realistic picture of what happens in real people's lives. You will take from the book what you chose because it allows you to draw your own conclusions. 
<br />
<br />It's a beautifully written book that tells many stories. It's not written in the style of many self help books that give you directions or exercises, this book just helps you to realize that we all have options. I found it very inspiring. Bronson does show both sides of the story that sometimes we fail in our attempts to find happiness but he also shows that if you stick to your intentions and don't let yourself be swayed by the material things in life, you can find happiness. Just like this book, life is all about what we make of it!</span>
                  
              
